01:35:33,546 --> 01:35:37,710
No, it's just that everything seems
to come at once.

1197
01:35:39,619 --> 01:35:42,782
The rest doesn't matter so much.
l can bear that.

1198
01:35:44,190 --> 01:35:47,887
But Laurie, l can never get over Laurie.

1199
01:35:48,962 --> 01:35:51,897
<i>Herr</i> Laurie, your friend.

1200
01:35:53,733 --> 01:35:55,997
-Something has happened to him?
-Yes.

1201
01:35:56,736 --> 01:35:59,796
No, something has happened to me.

1202
01:36:02,342 --> 01:36:07,837
He came to New York
and he didn't even come to see me.

1203
01:36:09,983 --> 01:36:12,076
What a fool he must be.

1204
01:36:14,621 --> 01:36:18,148
No, it's my fault. But l thought that....

1205
01:36:18,491 --> 01:36:20,982
What does it matter what l thought?

1206
01:36:21,094 --> 01:36:23,858
l've made a mess of it
as l do of everything.

1207
01:36:24,230 --> 01:36:28,496
But l have tried and when l think
of Aunt March taking Amy to Europe...

1208
01:36:28,568 --> 01:36:30,900
...when she always promised
she'd take me...

1209
01:36:31,204 --> 01:36:33,502
...not that l begrudge Amy the trip, but....

1210
01:36:33,673 --> 01:36:35,937
l suppose that's just what l am doing.

1211
01:36:36,009 --> 01:36:39,501
That trip to Europe
that you so looked forward to.

1212
01:36:39,579 --> 01:36:42,946
That is too bad.
That is a cruel disappointment, l know.

1213
01:36:43,016 --> 01:36:44,916
On top of it, that stupid professor.

1214
01:36:44,984 --> 01:36:47,179
He comes blundering
and makes things worse.

1215
01:36:47,253 --> 01:36:51,519
No. lf l can't stand the truth,
l'm not worth anything.

1216
01:36:52,325 --> 01:36:55,385
l didn't think those stories
were so very good.

1217
01:36:55,662 --> 01:36:57,129
But you see...

1218
01:36:58,364 --> 01:37:01,265
... <i>The Duke's Daughter</i>
paid the butcher's bill...

1219
01:37:01,501 --> 01:37:04,834
...and the <i>Curse of the Coventrys</i>
was the blessing of the Marches...

1220
01:37:05,171 --> 01:37:07,662
...because it sent Marmee and Beth
to the seashore.

1221
01:37:07,807 --> 01:37:09,832
Yes, that is what l have thought.

1222
01:37:10,376 --> 01:37:14,676
And then l have said to myself:
''l maybe have no right to speak.''

1223
01:37:15,915 --> 01:37:19,908
But then again, l said to myself:
''l maybe have no right to be silent.''

1224
01:37:20,286 --> 01:37:23,084
Miss March, you have talent.

1225
01:37:23,323 --> 01:37:26,520
-Do you really think so?
-Otherwise l could not say.

1226
01:37:26,626 --> 01:37:27,854
And you know that.

1227
01:37:28,328 --> 01:37:31,889
And l say to you,
''Sweep mud on the street first...

1228
01:37:32,465 --> 01:37:34,626
''...before you are false to that talent.''

1229
01:37:35,668 --> 01:37:37,158
Say to yourself:

1230
01:37:37,337 --> 01:37:42,297
''l will never write one single line
which l have not heard in my own heart.''

1231
01:37:43,610 --> 01:37:46,044
Say to yourself, ''While l am young...

1232
01:37:46,112 --> 01:37:50,378
''...l will write these simple,
beautiful things that l understand now.

1233
01:37:51,017 --> 01:37:56,512
''Maybe later, when l am a little older
and l have felt life more...

1234
01:37:56,756 --> 01:37:59,691
''...then l will write
about these poor wretches...

1235
01:38:00,160 --> 01:38:04,392
''...but l will make them live and breathe
like my Shakespeare did.''

1236
01:38:05,398 --> 01:38:08,492
-Will you do that, my little friend?
-Yes, l'll try.

1237
01:38:09,302 --> 01:38:12,100
But l don't think l'll ever be a Shakespeare,
do you?

1238
01:38:13,673 --> 01:38:15,868
But you can be a Josephine March.

1239
01:38:17,110 --> 01:38:20,079
And l assure you that is plenty.

1240
01:38:20,947 --> 01:38:24,542
And now,
don't be disappointed about that trip.

1241
01:38:26,119 --> 01:38:28,087
-Here.
-Peppermint, good.

1242
01:38:29,322 --> 01:38:32,382
Those of us who have been
all over the Old World...

1243
01:38:32,725 --> 01:38:35,216
...can find many things in the New...

1244
01:38:36,362 --> 01:38:39,331
...that are beautiful and young.

1245
01:38:48,174 --> 01:38:50,438
Miss March,
it would give me great pleasure...

1246
01:38:50,510 --> 01:38:54,173
...if l could show you some
of these things while you are here.

1247
01:38:54,247 --> 01:38:56,215
lf you would care to have so.

1248
01:38:57,917 --> 01:38:59,248
Thank you.

1249
01:39:02,722 --> 01:39:05,885
Then you are not angry
with the blundering professor...

1250
01:39:05,959 --> 01:39:08,359
...who takes the wrong times
for his lectures?

1251
01:39:08,728 --> 01:39:10,252
How could l be?

1252
01:39:13,900 --> 01:39:16,460
<i>Auf Wiedersehen</i>, my little friend.

1253
01:40:03,850 --> 01:40:05,181
Did you really like it?

1254
01:40:05,251 --> 01:40:07,617
-l never had such a....
-Happy, my little friend.

1255
01:40:07,687 --> 01:40:11,350
She was divine.
l don't want to be a writer anymore.

1256
01:40:11,658 --> 01:40:15,094
l want to be a wonderful singer
and thrill thousands of people...

1257
01:40:15,161 --> 01:40:19,154
...so that they cheer
and throw flowers at me like that.

1258
01:40:20,066 --> 01:40:21,590
Bravo. Bravo.

1259
01:40:23,336 --> 01:40:25,463
But l wouldn't make up my mind so soon...

1260
01:40:25,538 --> 01:40:28,371
...because at the art museum
you wanted to be a sculptress...

1261
01:40:28,441 --> 01:40:30,773
...at the circus you thought
the bareback rider...

1262
01:40:30,843 --> 01:40:33,004
...was the most beautiful thing
in the world.

1263
01:40:33,079 --> 01:40:35,104
l know, but to sing like that!

1264
01:40:44,424 --> 01:40:46,016
l forgot.

1265
01:40:46,159 --> 01:40:48,627
Something inside me tonight
makes me want to shout.

1266
01:40:48,695 --> 01:40:49,821
What would you shout?

1267
01:40:49,896 --> 01:40:54,959
l'd say, ''Look at me, world.
l'm Jo March and l'm so happy.''

1268
01:40:55,134 --> 01:40:57,329
My little friend, you are happy.

1269
01:40:58,037 --> 01:41:02,497
You haven't missed much lately
your home and your old friends?

1270
01:41:02,575 --> 01:41:04,600
But you're responsible for that.

1271
01:41:05,745 --> 01:41:08,077
Maybe they haven't missed me
so much either.

1272
01:41:08,147 --> 01:41:10,809
They're so busy with Meg
and those blessed babies.

1273
01:41:10,917 --> 01:41:13,078
Yes, how are those remarkable twins?

1274
01:41:13,186 --> 01:41:15,711
Wonderful. Meg's so proud of them.

1275
01:41:17,223 --> 01:41:19,157
Have you heard from Europe?

1276
01:41:19,392 --> 01:41:22,054
Nearly every boat
brings a letter from Amy.

1277
01:41:22,128 --> 01:41:24,255
And your friend...

1278
01:41:24,664 --> 01:41:26,723
...<i>Herr</i> Laurie, have you heard from him?

1279
01:41:27,500 --> 01:41:30,958
Only through Amy. They met at Vichy
and had a wonderful time together.

1280
01:41:31,971 --> 01:41:34,804
Miss March, l am bold to ask a favor.

1281
01:41:40,013 --> 01:41:42,243
Would you give me the address
of your father?

1282
01:41:42,415 --> 01:41:44,576
l wish to write him and ask him something.

1283
01:41:46,085 --> 01:41:48,576
Why, yes.
He'd be so happy to hear from you.

1284
01:41:48,855 --> 01:41:51,380
They almost know you.
l've told them all about you.

1285
01:41:51,457 --> 01:41:53,789
And they always ask after you
in their letters.

1286
01:41:53,860 --> 01:41:55,919
-Really?
-Yes, now l'll show you.

1287
01:41:56,696 --> 01:41:58,186
This is so nice.

1288
01:42:07,473 --> 01:42:08,804
Not l hope....

1289
01:42:10,810 --> 01:42:13,176
lt's Beth. She's....

1290
01:42:16,049 --> 01:42:18,517
l must go at once.

1291
01:42:18,785 --> 01:42:23,745
My friend, can l do something for you?
l'm sure there is something l can do.

1292
01:42:25,391 --> 01:42:29,418
No, there's nothing. Thank you.

1293
01:42:35,101 --> 01:42:36,728
Oh, Jo...

1294
01:42:37,537 --> 01:42:39,266
...to think you're home.

1295
01:42:40,606 --> 01:42:42,938
lf Amy were here, we'd all be together.

1296
01:42:45,311 --> 01:42:47,370
She'll be home in the spring, darling.

1297
01:42:49,048 --> 01:42:53,280
And l'm going to have you all well
and rosy by then.

1298
01:43:01,494 --> 01:43:05,555
Poor Jo, you mustn't be afraid.

1299
01:43:09,435 --> 01:43:11,266
Doesn't that sound funny...

1300
01:43:12,004 --> 01:43:15,633
...me saying that to you
when you've always said it to me?

1301
01:43:19,479 --> 01:43:21,276
You've always reminded me...

1302
01:43:22,615 --> 01:43:26,949
...of a seagull, strong and wild...

1303
01:43:27,753 --> 01:43:29,846
...and fond of the wind and the storm...

1304
01:43:30,823 --> 01:43:33,485
...dreaming of flying far out to sea.

1305
01:43:35,728 --> 01:43:39,459
And Mother always said
that l was like a little cricket...

1306
01:43:41,300 --> 01:43:43,666
...chirping contentedly on the hearth...

1307
01:43:44,837 --> 01:43:49,035
...never able to bear the thought
of leaving home.

1308
01:43:50,943 --> 01:43:52,535
But now...

1309
01:43:54,514 --> 01:43:55,674
...it's different.

1310
01:43:59,619 --> 01:44:01,314
l can't express it very well.

1311
01:44:01,921 --> 01:44:05,015
l shouldn't try to, to anyone but you...

1312
01:44:06,692 --> 01:44:10,685
...because l can't speak out
to anyone but my Jo.

1313
01:44:15,735 --> 01:44:17,259
l'm not afraid anymore.

1314
01:44:19,338 --> 01:44:25,743
l'm learning that l don't lose you,
that you'll be more to me than ever...

1315
01:44:27,013 --> 01:44:30,710
...and nothing can part us,
though it seems to.

1316
01:44:37,924 --> 01:44:38,913
Oh, Jo.

1317
01:44:40,826 --> 01:44:44,819
l think l'll be homesick for you
even in heaven.

1318
01:45:20,666 --> 01:45:22,031
The little loves.

1319
01:45:23,736 --> 01:45:26,728
-l'm afraid they're tiring you.
-Oh, no.

1320
01:45:28,174 --> 01:45:30,870
lt's time for my little regiment
to take its nap.

1321
01:45:47,126 --> 01:45:49,686
-They're sweet.
-Yes.

1322
01:45:54,600 --> 01:45:56,158
l think l can sleep now.

1323
01:46:01,007 --> 01:46:04,135
Look, Jo, my birds.

1324
01:46:05,077 --> 01:46:06,806
They got back in time.

1325
01:46:14,954 --> 01:46:18,321
-Bethie!
-Mother!

1326
01:46:20,660 --> 01:46:21,820
My daughter!

1327
01:46:21,894 --> 01:46:23,657
Bethie!

1328
01:46:29,335 --> 01:46:30,700
Oh, Marmee.

1329
01:46:33,773 --> 01:46:35,400
We mustn't cry.

1330
01:46:36,676 --> 01:46:39,338
We must be glad she's well at last.

1331
01:46:40,112 --> 01:46:41,773
No, Marmee, don't cry.

1332
01:46:56,395 --> 01:46:58,920
lf only there were another boat
leaving sooner.

1333
01:46:58,998 --> 01:47:03,059
Now, my dear, you've been so brave,
you must be patient.

1334
01:47:03,803 --> 01:47:06,636
We're going back on the very first boat.

1335
01:47:07,873 --> 01:47:11,138
l still think you should obey
your mother and stay.

1336
01:47:11,510 --> 01:47:15,640
l know. But l'm sick for home, Aunt March.
l hate all this now.

1337
01:47:16,382 --> 01:47:20,443
lf it weren't for this, l'd have been there,
at least to say goodbye.

1338
01:47:27,660 --> 01:47:30,185
Laurie, l knew you'd come.

1339
01:47:31,731 --> 01:47:33,164
My child!

1340
01:47:33,733 --> 01:47:35,394
Mr. Laurence!

1341
01:47:36,068 --> 01:47:40,164
Amy, we were in Germany,
and Marmee's letter had to be forwarded...

1342
01:47:40,840 --> 01:47:43,308
...but l came the moment l got it
because....

1343
01:47:43,776 --> 01:47:47,109
Well, you must comfort me now, too.

1344
01:47:53,786 --> 01:47:57,517
l'm so thankful you're here.
l haven't known what to do with the child.

1345
01:47:57,857 --> 01:47:59,791
Perhaps you can persuade her to stay.

1346
01:48:04,597 --> 01:48:07,395
-The elegant young matron.
-Hello, Jo, dear.

1347
01:48:07,466 --> 01:48:09,991
l've Sally Moffat's carriage.
l'm making some calls.

1348
01:48:10,069 --> 01:48:12,663
You want me to mind the demons
while you're gone?

1349
01:48:12,738 --> 01:48:14,365
No, l want you to go with me.

1350
01:48:14,540 --> 01:48:17,202
Jo, dear. lt's a lovely day
and l want to talk to you.

1351
01:48:17,276 --> 01:48:20,109
Talk to me now.
You know l can't bear calls.

1352
01:48:24,216 --> 01:48:27,185
-How's your story coming?
-Sent it off yesterday.

1353
01:48:27,553 --> 01:48:30,920
-Without us reading it?
-You can read it when they send it back.

1354
01:48:33,225 --> 01:48:35,318
-l had a letter from Amy.
-So did Marmee.

1355
01:48:36,162 --> 01:48:39,222
They're in Valrosa now
and she says it's paradise.

1356
01:48:41,801 --> 01:48:43,792
Jo, l'd like to ask you something.

1357
01:48:45,971 --> 01:48:48,064
l've been wondering...

1358
01:48:48,707 --> 01:48:50,504
...how would you feel...

1359
01:48:51,677 --> 01:48:55,545
...if you should hear that your Laurie
was learning to care for somebody else?

1360
01:48:59,318 --> 01:49:01,013
Meg, who?

1361
01:49:03,556 --> 01:49:04,523
Amy?

1362
01:49:07,827 --> 01:49:11,627
l don't know. l can't be sure.
l'm only reading between the lines.

1363
01:49:16,035 --> 01:49:17,935
Then you wouldn't mind?

1364
01:49:18,237 --> 01:49:20,432
No, Meg. How could l?

1365
01:49:21,540 --> 01:49:23,735
l think it would be wonderful, don't you?

1366
01:49:23,809 --> 01:49:25,800
Yes, but l wasn't quite sure.

1367
01:49:27,847 --> 01:49:29,678
Forgive me, dear...

1368
01:49:30,850 --> 01:49:35,412
...but l have so much
and you seem so alone.

1369
01:49:36,989 --> 01:49:39,617
l thought lately
that maybe if Laurie came back--

1370
01:49:39,725 --> 01:49:41,955
No, dear. lt's better as it is.

1371
01:49:42,061 --> 01:49:45,360
And l'm glad if he and Amy
are learning to love each other.

1372
01:49:46,098 --> 01:49:47,998
You're right about one thing though.

1373
01:49:48,100 --> 01:49:52,161
l am lonely and maybe
if Laurie had come back...

1374
01:49:53,005 --> 01:49:54,632
...l might've said yes.

1375
01:49:54,907 --> 01:49:58,104
Not because l love him any differently,
but because...

1376
01:49:59,311 --> 01:50:04,146
...it means more to me now
to be loved than it used to.

1377
01:50:38,484 --> 01:50:39,678
Laurie.

1378
01:50:40,786 --> 01:50:42,947
Oh, my Laurie!

1379
01:50:44,924 --> 01:50:47,688
Jo, dear. Are you glad to see me?

1380
01:50:48,827 --> 01:50:50,089
Glad?

1381
01:50:50,729 --> 01:50:56,065
My blessed boy!
Words can't express my gladness.

1382
01:50:56,368 --> 01:50:57,665
And where's your wife?

1383
01:50:57,736 --> 01:51:00,671
They all stopped in at Meg's,
but l couldn't wait to see you.

1384
01:51:00,739 --> 01:51:02,206
They'll be along presently.

1385
01:51:02,274 --> 01:51:04,538
Let me look at you.

1386
01:51:06,645 --> 01:51:09,773
Don't l look like a married man
and the head of a family?

1387
01:51:10,516 --> 01:51:15,920
Not a bit, and you never will, although
you have grown bigger and bonnier.

1388
01:51:16,589 --> 01:51:20,889
But you're the same scapegrace as ever,
despite that very elegant mustache.

1389
01:51:20,960 --> 01:51:25,329
-You can't fool me.
-You have to treat me with more respect.

1390
01:51:28,701 --> 01:51:33,832
Jo, dear, l want to say one thing,
then we'll put it by forever.

1391
01:51:34,006 --> 01:51:36,270
No, Laurie, please.

1392
01:51:37,543 --> 01:51:42,037
l think it was always meant to be,
you and Amy.

1393
01:51:43,082 --> 01:51:46,108
lt would have come about naturally
if only you'd waited.

1394
01:51:46,819 --> 01:51:48,878
As you tried to make me understand.

1395
01:51:49,521 --> 01:51:51,284
But you never could be patient.

1396
01:51:54,259 --> 01:51:57,751
So then we can go back
to the happy old times?

1397
01:51:57,830 --> 01:52:00,799
The way you wanted it,
when we first knew one another.

1398
01:52:04,503 --> 01:52:07,700
We never can be boy and girl again, Laurie.

1399
01:52:08,440 --> 01:52:11,102
Those happy old times can't come back.

1400
01:52:12,311 --> 01:52:14,074
We shouldn't expect them to.

1401
01:52:15,280 --> 01:52:18,977
We're man and woman now,
we can't be playmates any longer.

1402
01:52:20,552 --> 01:52:25,512
But we can be brother and sister,
to love and help one another...

1403
01:52:25,824 --> 01:52:28,918
...all the rest of our lives, can't we, Laurie?

1404
01:52:33,866 --> 01:52:35,299
There they are.

1405
01:52:35,668 --> 01:52:37,329
You look very well, Aunt March.

1406
01:52:37,403 --> 01:52:40,895
After the money spent on my rheumatism,
l come home on a day like this.

1407
01:52:41,073 --> 01:52:44,474
Heaven's to Betsy. lf she ain't dressed
in silk from head to foot.

1408
01:52:44,777 --> 01:52:47,371
Where is she? Where is Jo?

1409
01:52:49,348 --> 01:52:51,543
-Jo!
-Amy!

1410
01:52:51,684 --> 01:52:53,379
Doesn't she look marvelous, Jo?

1411
01:53:03,128 --> 01:53:06,427
l'll never forgive myself
for staying away so long...

1412
01:53:06,532 --> 01:53:09,968
...and leaving you
to bear everything all alone.

1413
01:53:10,269 --> 01:53:11,531
Darling.

1414
01:53:14,406 --> 01:53:19,036
To think that only yesterday we were
pulling our hair and buttoning pinafores.

1415
01:53:19,111 --> 01:53:22,478
And now she's a grown-up married lady
with a bustle.

1416
01:53:28,954 --> 01:53:31,582
You must be famished.
l'll help Hannah with the tea.

1417
01:53:31,657 --> 01:53:35,855
No, you won't, Marmee.
You'll sit right here. l'll help Hannah.

1418
01:53:43,435 --> 01:53:47,337
lt's fun, isn't it, Bethie?
Now that we're all together again.

1419
01:53:50,576 --> 01:53:53,977
Oh, dear. l've got to get some milk.
l haven't enough for my babies.

1420
01:53:54,046 --> 01:53:54,808
l'll go.

1421
01:53:54,880 --> 01:53:57,508
-But it's raining cats and dogs.
-l love it.

1422
01:53:57,716 --> 01:54:00,708
Sakes alive! There's the front doorbell.

1423
01:54:09,027 --> 01:54:11,825
-ls this the residence of Miss March?
-Why, yes.

1424
01:54:11,930 --> 01:54:13,488
-Miss Josephine March?
-Yes.

1425
01:54:13,766 --> 01:54:15,199
May l speak with her?

1426
01:54:15,267 --> 01:54:18,134
She's out,
but l'm expecting her back any minute.

1427
01:54:18,203 --> 01:54:20,194
-Won't you come in?
-Thank you.

1428
01:54:21,173 --> 01:54:23,869
No, thank you. She has guests, no.

1429
01:54:24,510 --> 01:54:26,171
Thank you very much.

1430
01:54:27,279 --> 01:54:33,115
But will you please give this to her
and tell her Professor Bhaer left it?

1431
01:54:33,919 --> 01:54:34,851
Thank you.

1432
01:54:35,020 --> 01:54:37,318
Professor Bhaer. Thank you very much.

1433
01:54:38,791 --> 01:54:41,191
-Goodbye.
-Goodbye.

1434
01:54:59,678 --> 01:55:02,010
-<i>Herr</i> Professor.
-My little friend.

1435
01:55:03,015 --> 01:55:05,245
l was just here to leave your book.

1436
01:55:05,617 --> 01:55:09,314
l wanted to tell you my friend published it,
and he has great hopes.

1437
01:55:09,488 --> 01:55:11,513
-He thinks--
-Never mind what he thinks.

1438
01:55:11,590 --> 01:55:12,682
Did you like it?

1439
01:55:12,758 --> 01:55:17,218
My little friend, it has such truth,
such simple beauty.

1440
01:55:17,296 --> 01:55:21,562
ln English quick,
l cannot tell you what it gives my heart.

1441
01:55:21,633 --> 01:55:23,760
But you were going without telling me.

1442
01:55:23,836 --> 01:55:26,634
lf l hadn't come back,
l never would've seen you again.

1443
01:55:27,039 --> 01:55:30,167
-Come, you're getting wet.
-l couldn't intrude. You have guests.

1444
01:55:30,242 --> 01:55:31,709
No, only my family.

1445
01:55:31,910 --> 01:55:33,468
My sister has just come home.

1446
01:55:33,545 --> 01:55:36,070
She is married to that boy l told you about.

1447
01:55:36,248 --> 01:55:38,182
-<i>Herr</i> Laurie?
-Yes.

1448
01:55:38,250 --> 01:55:41,276
This is the first time
we've all been together for a long time.

1449
01:55:41,353 --> 01:55:43,150
Please, just one moment before....

1450
01:55:43,222 --> 01:55:45,156
l had a wish to ask you something.

1451
01:55:45,858 --> 01:55:46,847
Would you....

1452
01:55:49,127 --> 01:55:51,220
l have no courage to think that....

1453
01:55:51,964 --> 01:55:54,398
But could l dare hope that....

1454
01:55:56,034 --> 01:55:59,333
l know l shouldn't make so free as to ask.

1455
01:56:01,106 --> 01:56:06,100
l have nothing to give but my heart so full
and these empty hands.

1456
01:56:08,013 --> 01:56:10,277
Not empty now.

1457
01:56:11,583 --> 01:56:13,346
Heart's dearest!

1458
01:56:21,827 --> 01:56:23,294
Welcome home.

